text.tspan: To calculate the position of Mars at the time of launch,
subtract the amount of its motion during the spacecrafts
travel time ( 135.555 degrees) from its point of arrival.
Considering that launch from Earth was at the Hohmann
orbit perihelion (point closest to the sun) and arrival is at
the Hohmann orbit aphelion (point farthest from the sun),
we can conclude that a launch opportunity occurs when
Mars is 44.445 degrees ahead of Earth in its orbit.
